    <!-- ============= HOW IT'S DONE ============= -->
    <section class="how container">
      <h2>How is a hair transplantation done?</h2>

      <div class="how-row">
        <h3>FUE – Follicular Unit Extraction</h3>
        <p> During the FUE technique, individual follicles are extracted from the donor region and precisely implanted
          into targeted areas using micro-slits or implanter pens — offering a minimally invasive approach with
          negligible scarring and rapid recovery.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="how-row">
        <h3>DHI – Direct Hair Implantation</h3>
        <p>In the DHI technique, hair follicles are directly implanted using a specialized implanter pen (such as the
          Choi Pen). This advanced method allows precise, angle-controlled placement and higher graft density —
          resulting in natural, fuller, and long-lasting outcomes.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============= FUE DETAIL ============= -->
    <section class="fue-detail container">
      <div class="fue-img">
        <img src="/img/men-img1.png" alt="">
      </div>
      <div class="fue-copy">
        <p>FUE is a minimally invasive technique where individual hair grafts are gently extracted using a motorized
          punch and implanted into micro-sites that mimic your natural growth pattern. This precise method enhances
          graft survival, ensures aesthetic harmony, and minimizes scalp trauma.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============= DENSE IMPLANTATION ============= -->
    <section class="dense container">
      <div class="dense-copy">
        <h2>Dense Hair Implantation</h2>
      <p> After harvesting through the FUE technique, we perform high-precision implantation under magnification using
          ultra-fine pilot incisions — up to 30% smaller than standard implanters. This method ensures dense,
          natural-looking results by maintaining perfect control over graft depth, angle, and direction.</p>

      </div>
      <div class="dense-img">
        <img src="/img/men-img2.webp" alt="">
